&lt;h3 id=&quot;Problem-Statement&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#Problem-Statement&quot; class=&quot;headerlink&quot; title=&quot;Problem Statement&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Problem Statement&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;We have $N$ pieces of ropes, numbered 1 through  $N$. The length of piece $i$ is $a_i$.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;At first, for each $i(1≤i≤N−1)$, piece $i$ and piece $i+1$ are tied at the ends, forming one long rope with  $N-1$ knots. Snuke will try to untie all of the knots by performing the following operation repeatedly:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Choose a (connected) rope with a total length of at least $L$, then untie one of its knots.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Is it possible to untie all of the $N−1$ knots by properly applying this operation? If the answer is positive, find one possible order to untie the knots.&lt;/p&gt;
    
